## Consumption by Validator [ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws](https://ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/web/direct-files/collection_f23499fa-f1b8-4d9d-a78b-1d96ca262e69/9abc2844-b527-41a6-984d-30e8698958eb/invariants-8Xz_1YHRT1W1xd_tCBpMyA.md)

The Rust validator uses this file as a declarative contract rather than as executable configuration.  On startup or at build time, it can scan the frontmatter to determine which tags are active and map each `id` to the corresponding `check_fn` implementation already compiled into `validator.rs`. [ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws](https://ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/web/direct-files/collection_f23499fa-f1b8-4d9d-a78b-1d96ca262e69/9abc2844-b527-41a6-984d-30e8698958eb/invariants-8Xz_1YHRT1W1xd_tCBpMyA.md)

In practice, this allows:

- AI systems to understand which invariants exist and how they fail without reading Rust code. [ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws](https://ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/web/direct-files/collection_f23499fa-f1b8-4d9d-a78b-1d96ca262e69/9abc2844-b527-41a6-984d-30e8698958eb/invariants-8Xz_1YHRT1W1xd_tCBpMyA.md)
- CI and tooling to cross-check that every tag ID referenced in commits, frontmatter, or manifests has a documented behavior here. [ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws](https://ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/web/direct-files/collection_f23499fa-f1b8-4d9d-a78b-1d96ca262e69/9abc2844-b527-41a6-984d-30e8698958eb/invariants-8Xz_1YHRT1W1xd_tCBpMyA.md)
- Future extensions to add new tags or deprecate existing ones by updating this specification and the corresponding Rust functions in lock-step. [ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws](https://ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/web/direct-files/collection_f23499fa-f1b8-4d9d-a78b-1d96ca262e69/9abc2844-b527-41a6-984d-30e8698958eb/invariants-8Xz_1YHRT1W1xd_tCBpMyA.md)
